Death Toll in German Gas Blast Rises to Nine 
Rescuers have found nine bodies from the rubbles of a house for the
aged in the northern German city of Bremen, according to reports
reaching here.
The four-story house collapsed in the wake of a powerful gas explosion
on Monday morning, which also heavily damaged several adjoining houses.
Six bodies were identified and they were three women and three men at
ages between 90 to 61.
Two of the 31 residents in the care center owned by the religious
charity organization Salvation Army were still missing. 21 residents
were injured in the incident, including five people living in nearby
houses.
Local authorities believed that the explosion occurred in the basement
and there was speculation that it was caused by gas leak stemming from
unauthorized tinkering of the gas pipe.
